# React Hooks Patterns

## Hook Design Rules

- Every hook must accept generic type parameters for type-safe payloads
- Return tuple or object with clear naming: `[data, { mutate, status, error }]`
- Memoize returned objects/arrays with `useMemo`/`useCallback` to prevent re-renders
- Clean up subscriptions in `useEffect` return functions

## Provider Pattern

```typescript
// OfflineProvider must wrap the app and accept OfflineConfig
// Use React.createContext with a meaningful error for missing provider
const ctx = createContext<OfflineEngine | null>(null);
function useEngine(): OfflineEngine {
  const engine = useContext(ctx);
  if (!engine) throw new Error('Wrap your app in <OfflineProvider>');
  return engine;
}
```

## Hook Naming

- `useOfflineStatus` - returns `{ isOnline: boolean }`
- `useOfflineQuery<T>` - cache-first data reading
- `useOfflineMutation<T>` - write with offline queue
- `useSyncStatus` - returns `{ status, progress, lastSyncAt }`
- `usePendingQueue` - returns pending actions list

## Platform Compatibility

- Hooks must work in both React DOM and React Native
- No DOM-specific APIs (`document`, `window`) inside hooks
- No React Native-specific APIs inside hooks
- Platform concerns are handled by adapters injected via config
